@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{tomo}}}} is used after numbers and counters to mean "both", "all (three)" etc.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KT{{se-ta-}}ha2@FG{{@KJ{{sheet*of...}}:mai}}@EM{{tomo}}}}M@HI{{@KT{{saizu}}desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Are both of these sweaters mediums?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{tomo}}}} is used after the @HI{{ku}} form of an adjective to indicate an approximate maximum or minimum.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KJ{{house}}nara,@KJ{{few}}naku@EM{{tomo}}1@KJ{{hundred*million^circle}}hasurudeshou.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This house would cost at least 100 million yen.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{tomo}}}} can indicate inclusion.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{sa-bisu}}@KJ{{fee}}@EM{{tomo}}@FG{{@KJ{{fit^plot}}:goukei}}1@KJ{{ten*thousand}}5000@KJ{{circle}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The total is &yen;15,000 including the service charge.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
After a verb in the volitional, @EM{{@HI{{tomo}}}} adds emphasis to a supposition.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{bright^day}}ha@KJ{{snow}}ga@KJ{{descend}}rou@EM{{tomo}},@KJ{{going}}kutsumorida.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Even if it should snow tomorrow, I intend to go.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{tomo}}}}@HI{{arou}}@N{{}}@HI{{ga}} carries the meaning "of all people/things". 

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{neck^inter-}}:shushou}}@EM{{tomo}}arou@KJ{{person}}ga,son'nakotowoshite
      @FG{{@KJ{{even^spirit}}:heiki}}datoha@FG{{@KJ{{faith}}:shin}}jirarenai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      For the prime minister, of all people, to do something like that and be calm about it is unbelievable.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{tomo}}}} after two words of opposite meaning and followed by @HI{{@KJ{{say}}enai}} it means "can't say X or Y".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{sono@FG{{@KJ{{price^grade}}:nedann}}ha,@KJ{{tall}}i@EM{{tomo}}@KJ{{relax}}i@EM{{tomo}}@KJ{{say}}emansen'ne.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It is hard to say whether the price is high or low.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
At the end of a sentence, @EM{{@HI{{tomo}}}} adds decisiveness to a positive statement.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{@KJ{{bright^day}}no@FG{{@KJ{{test^fit}}:shiai}}ni@KJ{{going}}kimasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{@KJ{{going}}ku@EM{{tomo}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: Are you going to the game tomorrow.
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: I certainly am.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

